{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500722","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500722"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:17:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:17:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1665"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1665","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1665"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.71,0.11,0.07,0.01,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1665"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"30480"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1665","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1665"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1665"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"16422"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"435"},{"type":"tags","id":"9022"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2285"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2387"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"30480","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/30480"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents with a two hour history of sudden and painless loss of vision in his right eye. There is no history of eye problems. The patient takes perindopril for hypertension, and glibenclamide for type 2 diabetes mellitus. Visual acuity is counting fingers in the right eye and 6/6 in the left eye. At fundoscopy there are haemorrhages in all four quadrants of the retina, with venous dilatation and oedema of the optic disc.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Central retinal vein occlusion","Central retinal artery occlusion","Retinal detachment","Macular degeneration","Proliferative diabetic retinopathy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ESudden onset of painless vision loss accompanied by retinal haemorrhages and optic disc oedema is consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Ecentral retinal vein occlusion\u003C/strong\u003E. Central retinal artery occlusion can also present with sudden painless vision loss, however the retina will show pallor and a \u0027cherry red\u0027 spot at the macula. Retinal detachment will usually present with flashes and floaters and the retina will show \u0027wrinkled\u0027 appearance with appropriate field loss. Macular degeneration does not present with acute painless vision loss. Proliferative diabetic retinopathy can cause a tractional retinal detachment leading to painless vision loss. The retina will however show evidence of microaneurysms, dot-blot haemorrhages and cotton wool spots.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Sudden onset of painless loss of vision must raise the possibility of a local vascular event."],"references":["Bowling, B. (2015). Kanski\u2019s clinical ophthalmology (8th ed.). W B Saunders."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"16422"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1665"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"16422","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/16422"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2022-11-30T12:22:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2022-11-30T12:22:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1665"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"30480"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attribut